The government is expected to collect a projected about $2 billion in annual revenues from a proposed development of the Block 6 oil field started in 2010. [48] On July 26, 2012, Minister of Minas’ José Jail and Exploration Pty announced that Block 6 oil production is projecting to yield to $10 billion in oil revenues. [52]

The country also has significant natural gas reserves, which remains undeveloped due to the lack of an energy infrastructure in the archipelago. The two gas fields, Memé and Purris, are located southwest of the capital city of Sao Tome. The first natural gas field, Memé, holds an estimated 30 billion cubic meters (Mm3) of gas offshore, and Purris is estimated to hold 280Mm3. [47]

As a result of a developing oligopolistic market, a majority of Sao Tome’s energy still comes from diesel fuel despite abundant supply options offshore. This is primarily because of the country’s heavy reliance on vehicles rather than alternative public transportation. [47]

Environmental threats and opportunity. The issues of not being able to collect sufficient garbage coverage from urban and rural areas, resulting in mosquitoes breeding grounds, is a major environmental concern, especially with the onset of the rainy season.
